elements.content: We have prepared a family of [WS3Cu2]-based coordination polymers with a rare μ-N type coordination by a simple one-pot assembly of [Et4N]­[Tp*WS3] (1) with CuCN in the presence of pyridine (py), 4,4′-bipyridine (bipy), 1,2-bis­(4-pyridyl)­ethane (bpea), and 2,4,6-tri­(4-pyridyl)-1,3,5-triazine (tpt) at room temperature. The resulting coordination polymers [Tp*WS3Cu2­(CN)­(μ-py)]2·py (2·py), [Tp*WS3Cu2­(CN)2­Cu­(μ-py)2]2­·3py (3·3py), [Et4N]­[{Tp*WS3­(CuCN)2Cu}2­(CN)­(μ4-bipy)] (4), [Tp*WS3Cu2­(CN)­(μ4-bpea)0.5]2­·CH2Cl2 (5·CH2Cl2), and [Tp*WS3Cu2­(CN)­(μ6-tpt)1/3]2 (6) share a butterfly-shaped [Tp*WS3Cu2] motif with sizable concave to accommodate pyridyl ligands. The approximate mirror symmetry of the motif also induces the orthogonal coalignment of the pyridyl ligands, reinforcing a unique μ-type association with the Cu centers of the cluster skeleton. Such a coordination mode, though scarce in general coordination chemistry, is universal in our series with good ligand tolerance including ligand size and symmetry. In addition, each butterfly-shaped [Tp*WS3Cu2] motif is linked by CN (2), Cu­(CN)2 (3), Cu2(CN)5/μ4-bipy (4), CN/μ4-bpea (5), and CN/μ6-tpt (6) to yield diverse polydimensional structures showing one-dimensional zigzag chains (2 and 3), two-dimensional networks (4 and 5), and a three-dimensional net (6). The third-order nonlinear optical (NLO) property of 2–6 in DMF measured using a Z-scan technique at 532 nm demonstrated that 2–6 have a reverse saturable absorption and self-focusing effects with the hyperpolarizability γ values in the range of 6.32 × 10–30 esu to 9.82 × 10–30 esu. Such values are remarkably larger than that of their precursor complex 1 (1.07 × 10–32 esu). The results provide an interesting insight into how the μ-type coordination mode of N-donor ligands affects the self-assembly of the [Tp*WS3Cu2]-supported coordination polymers and their structural topologies, as well as their third-order NLO performances.

Introduction

Pyridyl ligands, such as the parent pyridine (py) and 4,4'-bipyridine (bipy), are among the most utilized donors in coordination chemistry, either as auxiliary ligands to satisfy the geometrical needs of the metal centers, or as bridging ligands to link metal centers into extended arrays. Their coordination mode can be comfortably assumed to be monodentate, although the μ- and π-type coordination modes are not unknown. We herein present a series of [WS3Cu2]-supported coordination polymers in which pyridyl ligands, including py, bipy, 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethane (bpea), and 2,4,6-tri(4-pyridyl)-1,3,5-triazine (tpt), feature a μ-N coordination universally (). This unusual coordination mode is made possible by the butterfly type cluster core [Tp*WS3Cu2] (Tp* = hydridotris(3,5-dimethylpyrazol-1-yl)borate), which contains a deep, symmetrical concave to accommodate the orthogonally aligned pyridyls. This is particularly so for the higher dimension polymers achieved with the C 3 symmetrical Tp* ligand. Using the trigonal symmetrical Tp ligand (Tp = hydridotris(pyrazol-1-yl)borate) to constrain the cubane cluster of [TpMoS4Fe3Cl3] that was subsequently converted to the nitrogenase PN-type cluster mimic [Mo2Fe6S9] has been elegantly described by Holm et al.

elements.content: The present work is a systematic follow-up of our previous, serendipitous observation that a one-pot assembly of [Tp*WS3]−, CuCN and bipy yielded a 2D coordination polymer of [Tp*WS3Cu2­(CN)­(μ4-bipy)0.5] featuring μ4-bipy linkages. Herein we further demonstrate that, with the presence of the butterfly-shaped [Tp*WS3Cu2] cluster core, the μ-N coordination of pyridyl appears to be universal and applicable to ligands with a wide range of size and symmetry, as evidenced from the class of polymeric compounds isolated, viz, [Tp*WS3Cu2CN­(μ-py)]2·py (2·py), [Tp*WS3Cu2­(CN)2Cu­(μ-py)2]2­·3py (3·3py), [Et4N]­[{Tp*WS3­(CuCN)2Cu}2(CN)­(μ4-bipy)] (4), [Tp*WS3Cu2­(CN)­(μ4-bpea)0.5]2­·CH2Cl2 (5·CH2Cl2), and [Tp*WS3Cu2­(CN)­(μ6-tpt)1/3]2 (6). In all these cases, the presence of the μ-N coordination elevated the dimensionality of the polymers. The μ6-tpt, for example, juxtaposes three cluster cores to produce a rare three-dimensional (3D) cluster-supported coordination polymer. Relative to that of 1, compounds 2–6 in the DMF solution display larger third-order nonlinear optical (NLO) responses in Z-scan experiments at 532 nm, with the hyperpolarizability γ values confined in between 6.32 × 10–30 esu and 9.82 × 10–30 esu. In this article, we report the synthesis and structural characterization of 2–6 together with their NLO properties in DMF solution.

elements.content: For compound 2, the residual peak with the highest magnitude for the solvated py molecule was assigned as the N atom, and the molecule was subsequently refined as a rigid hexagon with occupancy factors for all atoms fixed at 0.50 to obtain reasonable thermal factors. For 3, one of the solvated py containing N12 and C33–C37 lies on a special position of higher symmetry than the molecule can possess. It was treated as a spatial disorder by applying PART –1 and PART 0 in the .ins file with the site occupation factors changed to 0.50 for these atoms. The py ring was also refined as a rigid hexagon. For the other two free py solvates, the N atoms were assigned by inspecting the possible interactions with their neighboring atoms. For 4, N2/C2 displayed occupational disorder and the occupancies for these domains were fixed at 0.50 each, followed by applying EXYZ and EADP for this disordered pair. The weakly associated bipy lies on a special position of higher symmetry than the molecule can possess. It was treated as spatial disorder by applying PART – 1 and PART 0 in the .ins file with the site occupation factors further changed to 0.25 for these atoms to obtain reasonable thermal factors. Charge counting revealed that a cation with 0.25 occupancy is missing. Results and Discussion

Synthesis and Spectral Aspects

Mixing [Et4N][Tp*WS3] (1) with 2 equiv of CuCN at room temperature with stirring provided a red solution accompanied by a small amount of red precipitate which was removed by filtration. The solvent was evaporated to give a dark-red solid that was recrystallized from pyridine to yield [Tp*WS3Cu2(CN)(μ-py)]2⋅py (2⋅py) as dark-red blocks in 59% yield. The corresponding reaction of 1, but with 3 equiv of CuCN and NH4PF6 at 80 °C yielded a large amount of red precipitate. This precipitate was partly dissolved in py to form a red solution which was filtered. Diethyl ether diffusion into the filtrate provided [Tp*WS3Cu2(CN)2Cu(μ-py)2]2⋅3py (3⋅3py) in 23% yield. The low yield of 3⋅3py was probably due to the poor solubility of CuCN in CH2Cl2/MeCN. During our experiments, we found that the presence of NH4PF6 is critical in providing the product as good quality crystals. With the absence of NH4PF6, the products cannot be formed. Thus, the presence of NH4PF6 is likely to provide an ionic environment to facilitate crystallization. Substituting pyridine with bipy, bpea, and tpt in the synthetic procedure for 2 yielded two two-dimensional (2D) coordination polymers [Et4N][{Tp*WS3(CuCN)2Cu}2(CN)(μ4-bipy)] (4), [Tp*WS3Cu2(CN)(μ4-bpea)0.5]2⋅CH2Cl2 (5⋅CH2Cl2), and one 3D coordination polymer [Tp*WS3Cu2(CN)(μ6-tpt)1/3]2 (6), respectively. Compounds 2-6 lost crystallinity and gradually become amorphous under aerobic conditions within a few days. Nonetheless, their elemental analysis and IR results suggested no obvious change compared to the fresh single crystals.

elements.content: The IR spectra of 2–6 revealed the CN and W–S bond vibrations at 2121 and 417 cm–1 for 2, 2135 and 415 cm–1 for 3, 2129 and 412 cm–1 for 4, 2160 and 426 cm–1 for 5, and 2160 and 416 cm–1 for 6. The UV–vis spectra of 2–6 gave intense bands at about 310 nm, resembling those in 1 (), suggesting that these bands are ascribed to ligand-to-metal charge transfer (LMCT) in the [Tp*WS3] moiety. Under ESI-MS conditions, 2–6 disintegrated into a variety of cationic species. In their positive-ion ESI-MS spectra, peaks at m/z values of 731.9 (2, 4, 6), 758.9 (3, 4, 5, 6), 793.9 (3, 4), 820.9 (4), 1460.8 (3, 4, 5), 1524.8 (3), and 1613.7 (3, 4, 5) can be assigned as [Tp*WS3Cu2(CN)­H]+ (2, 4, 6), [Tp*WS3Cu2­(CN)2H2]+ (3, 4, 5, 6), [Tp*WS3Cu2­(CuCN)]+ (3, 4), [Tp*WS3Cu2­(CuCN) (CN)­H]+ (4), [(Tp*WS3Cu2CN)2H]+ (3, 4, 5), [(Tp*WS3­Cu2CN)2Cu]+ (3), and [(Tp*WS3Cu2CuCN)2­(CN)]+ (3, 4, 5). These peaks match well with the simulated isotopic patterns (Figures S2–S6). The absence of pyridyl ligands in these spectra is also notable. Such an observation indicates that the coordination of CN ligands to Cu center in these cluster fragments is strong enough to hinder any pyridyl association, corroborating our early examples wherein CN is used as the only bridging ligands. Producing these species using certain ionization techniques followed by their enrichment may have the potential to pave the way toward novel W/Cu/S/CN clusters and is our future incentive. The structures of 2–6 are authenticated via X-ray crystallography.

elements.content: Complex 2·py crystallizes in the monoclinic P21/c space group. Its local structure consists of one [Tp*WS3Cu2­(CN)­(μ-py)] and one free py molecule. The cluster unit in 2 features a butterfly-shaped [Tp*WS3Cu2]+ core structure wherein each Cu is tetrahedrally coordinated by one N atom from the py ligand, one C atom from CN and two S atoms (). elements.content: Compound 3·3py crystallizes in the monoclinic P21/n space group. Its local structure contains one [Tp*WS3Cu2(CN)2­(μ-py)­Cu­(py)2] unit and one py solvent molecule. The cluster unit in 3 has a butterfly-shaped core resembling that of 2·py. elements.content: Compound 4 crystallizes in the monoclinic C2/m space group. Its local structure comprises half of one [Tp*WS3Cu2(CN)2­Cu­(CN)0.5] cluster, a [Et4N]+ cation and a bipy molecule, both with 0.25 occupancy. As shown in , each Cu atom of the [Tp*WS3Cu2] core is coordinated by two S atoms, one CN, and one N atom to supply a tetrahedral geometry. Every two [Tp*WS3Cu2] cores are connected by a pair of [Cu­(CN)3]2– bridges to form a macrocyclic dimer (a). This dimer can be equally treated as two [Tp*WS3Cu2(CN)2] cores linked by a pair of CuCN metalloligands. Each macrocycle is joined by a CN ligand to the next to form a 1D necklace-like chain extended along the b direction (b). The “isolated” Cu center is trigonally coordinated by three bridging CN ligands. The nonconventional [WS3Cu2] + [Cu] combination in 3 is thus repeated in the current case as ([WS3Cu2] + [Cu])2. Similar to the structure of 2, each N atom from bipy was found to bridge two Cu atoms within the same butterfly-shaped [Tp*WS3Cu2]+ core by weak interactions (2.4944(2) Å and 2.6596(2) Å). The bipy is therefore coordinated in a μ4-N fashion with two pairs of Cu atoms from two cluster cores (b,c). To our knowledge, there has been only one example of this type of bonding reported previously, [Tp*WS3Cu2(CN)­(μ4-bipy)0.5]. This rare μ4 coordination mode is probably due to the association of the two CN bridges with the two Cu centers in the butterfly-shaped [Tp*WS3Cu2] core which sterically “squeezes” the bipy ligand into close proximity of adjacent Cu centers. Each bipy in turn connects two [Tp*WS3Cu2]+ clusters from two 1D chains in the c direction, and thus a 2D grid forms in the bc plane (d). The difference between 4 and [Tp*WS3Cu2(CN)­(bipy)0.5] also featuring a μ4-bipy is that the cluster dimers in 4 propagate via the connections to single Cu ions as anchors to give necklace-shaped chains, whereas in [Tp*WS3Cu2(CN)­(bipy)0.5], the butterfly-shaped clusters propagate via direct association with CN ligands into zigzag-type chains.

Each Cu center in the cluster core is tetrahedrally coordinated by two S atoms, one N from tpt and another N (or C) from a CN ligand. elements.content: In this work, we demonstrated that the rare cases of μ-N bridging observed in this series of [Tp*WS3Cu2]-supported coordination polymers 2–6 is facilitated by the shape and symmetry of the butterfly-shaped cluster core as well as the coordination flexibility of Cu­(I) centers. This assertion is counter-supported by that pyridyls exhibit normal bonding in coordination polymers supported by other types of cluster units. The C 3 symmetrical Tp* ligands may also contribute to this behavior, reminiscent of the noninnocent nature of Tp and Tp* in the formation of cuboidal [MoS4Fe3Cl3]-type clusters. It is noteworthy that through the use of monotopic (py), ditopic (bipy and bpea), and tritopic (tpt) ligands, the dimensionality of the resulting coordination polymers goes from 1D (2, 3) through 2D (4, 5) to 3D (6). The Cu−μ-N bond distances are marginally longer than normal, indicating a rather weak association. This weak association is probably the cause of void collapse of the porous coordination polymer of 6 which excludes gas uptake. Nevertheless, such weak associations can be important for providing preoccupied binding sites in catalytic conversions, or potentially unsaturated sites for guest interactions. Our preliminary observations also suggest that such a μ-N type coordination is a kinetic outcome and that the structural outcome at elevated temperatures becomes “normal” but still interesting. Compounds 2–6 demonstrate good third-order NLO performance using Z-scan technique under 532 nm and 21 ps conditions, with their γ values being 590–900 times higher than that of 1. Because 2–6 possess the same butterfly-shaped [Tp*WS3Cu2] cluster cores in their structures, the improved but somewhat different NLO performances is mainly due to the strong coordination among Cu­(I) centers and the S atoms of 1 and the formation of the 1D, 2D, and 3D coordination polymer architectures. Even larger γ values might be expected if these cluster units could be cultivated into more stable and larger-size molecular entities, and we are working on these challenges.

Conclusions

In this work, we demonstrated that the rare cases of μ-N bridging observed in this series of [Tp*WS3Cu2]-supported coordination polymers 2-6 is facilitated by the shape and symmetry of the butterfly-shaped cluster core as well as the coordination flexibility of Cu(I) centers. This assertion is counter-supported by that pyridyls exhibit normal bonding in coordination polymers supported by other types of cluster units. The C 3 symmetrical Tp* ligands may also contribute to this behavior, reminiscent of the noninnocent nature of Tp and Tp* in the formation of cuboidal [MoS4Fe3Cl3]-type clusters. It is noteworthy that through the use of monotopic (py), ditopic (bipy and bpea), and tritopic (tpt) ligands, the dimensionality of the resulting coordination polymers goes from 1D (2, 3) through 2D (4, 5) to 3D (6). The Cu-μ-N bond distances are marginally longer than normal, indicating a rather weak association. This weak association is probably the cause of void collapse of the porous coordination polymer of 6 which excludes gas uptake. Nevertheless, such weak associations can be important for providing preoccupied binding sites in catalytic conversions, or potentially unsaturated sites for guest interactions. Our preliminary observations also suggest that such a μ-N type coordination is a kinetic outcome and that the structural outcome at elevated temperatures becomes "normal" but still interesting. Compounds 2-6 demonstrate good third-order NLO performance using Z-scan technique under 532 nm and 21 ps conditions, with their γ values being 590-900 times higher than that of 1. Because 2-6 possess the same butterfly-shaped [Tp*WS3Cu2] cluster cores in their structures, the improved but somewhat different NLO performances is mainly due to the strong coordination among Cu(I) centers and the S atoms of 1 and the formation of the 1D, 2D, and 3D coordination polymer architectures. Even larger γ values might be expected if these cluster units could be cultivated into more stable and larger-size molecular entities, and we are working on these challenges.
